      	<div source="bib:Hultzsch1902-1903_01" type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
      		<p>
      			In the seventeenth year <supplied reason="subaudible">of the reign</supplied> of king Vijaya-Īśvaravarman, when Kaṉaiyūr fell into the possession of the enemies, Cāttaṉ of Pūtūr himself, the servant of Kāṭṭiṟai, was cut down.
      		</p><!--Update to DHARMA TG rules: Daḍiya, Kaṉṉāḍakas + statement on translation-->
      	</div>
      	
         <div type="commentary">
         	<p>Hultzsch: fn6: māṟṟu seems to be used in the sense of māṟṟār, ‘enemies.’</p><!--update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: "Unlike other vīrakkals, the stone bears no sculptures of any kind." Untrue. See slab in Chennai Government Museum (acc. no. 2160/78). Hultzsch worked with estampages of the inscriptions only.</p><!--update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: Īśvaravarman = Gaṅga-Pallava</p><!--update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: kāṭṭiṟai, "king of the forester" = synonym of kāṭavaṉ, "forester".</p><!--update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: Pūtūr = hamlet of Pennagaram.</p><!--update-->
         	<p>Hultzsch: māṟṟu seemingly used in the sense of māṟṟār, "enemies".</p><!--update-->
         	<p>See tfaPallava513, same slab (right of the present inscription).</p><!--update-->
         </div>
      	
